Psychological self-report and trait measures indicate a mixed profile with several signals that point toward elevated perceived stress. The participant reports a relatively high trait anxiety score (STAI = 50, Z = 0.86) — one of the strongest survey-level correlates of PSS in the study (correlation ≈ 0.31) — suggesting a greater propensity to experience and report feelings of anxiety and stress. Current depressive symptoms are low–moderate (CES-D = 10, Z = -0.34) and thus do not strongly push toward higher perceived stress in this case, while self-esteem is relatively high (RSES Z = 0.82), a factor that is inversely associated with PSS (corr ≈ -0.16) and would be expected to buffer stress perception. Self-rated happiness is lower than average (Current happiness Z = -0.53), and subjective sleep quality is impaired (PSQI = 7, classified as disturbed sleep), both of which are modestly consistent with higher perceived stress in the sample. Alcohol use at the reported frequency (beer and wine/liquor 1–2 times per week) is above average for this cohort (Z ≈ 1.0) but shows negligible correlation with PSS in the study. In sum, trait anxiety and disturbed subjective sleep are the strongest self-report indicators that would point toward elevated perceived stress, while higher self-esteem provides partial counterweight.

Wearable-derived sleep and circadian physiology provide additional, largely non-conflicting information. Nighttime heart rate deviations show pronounced reductions overnight and a low resting heart rate (52.4 bpm, Z = -0.68), consistent with relatively low basal physiological arousal; these physiological features have only small positive correlations with PSS in the sample (resting HR corr ≈ 0.14). Circadian rhythm analysis shows a relatively large amplitude (Z = 0.64) and reasonably stable day-to-day structure (interdaily stability near average, Z = 0.09; intradaily variability lower than average, Z = -0.53). Higher amplitude and lower intradaily fragmentation are associated with slightly lower perceived stress in the cohort (correlations ≈ -0.17 and +0.16 respectively), so the participant’s stronger amplitude and lower fragmentation are features consistent with lower or average perceived stress. Objective sleep duration is slightly below the sample mean (median 6 h 34 min, Z = -0.77) with low nap frequency and relatively consistent sleep start times (median start ≈ 01:45 AM, SD ~56 min, Zs modestly negative), a pattern that signals shorter and later nocturnal sleep but regularity across nights. The subjective sleep disturbance (PSQI) combined with objectively shorter, late sleep could contribute to higher perceived stress, whereas the preserved circadian amplitude and low fragmentation point toward resilient behavioral-physiological structure.

Weighing evidence across modalities yields a mixed but asymmetric picture: the strongest predictors of higher PSS in this participant are elevated trait anxiety and disturbed subjective sleep coupled with lower self-reported happiness. Countervailing signals include high self-esteem, high health satisfaction, low resting heart rate, high circadian amplitude, and low intradaily variability — features that in the cohort are modestly associated with lower or average PSS. Because trait anxiety (STAI) is among the most strongly correlated predictors of PSS in this dataset and is meaningfully elevated here (Z ≈ 0.86), and because subjective sleep disturbance and lower happiness also align with higher stress, the overall balance of evidence favors the participant having perceived stress in the upper half of the study distribution. Therefore the participant is more likely to fall into the top 50% of PSS scores rather than the bottom 50%.

