Self-report measures indicate a mixed but overall modest symptom burden in domains linked to perceived stress. Depressive symptoms (CES-D = 8, Z = -0.55) are below the sample mean and classified as “not depressed,” and global self-esteem is near the sample average (RSES = 38, Z = -0.03). Trait anxiety (STAI–Trait = 43, Z = 0.17) is mildly above the sample mean; this measure has a positive correlation with PSS in the sample (r ≈ 0.31), so the modestly elevated trait anxiety constitutes one source of risk for greater perceived stress. Subjective sleep quality is on the borderline of disturbance (PSQI = 6, classified “Disturbed Sleep,” Z = -0.33), but this PSQI value is only slightly elevated and its z-score is below the group mean. Self-reported happiness is above average (score = 4, Z = 0.55) and general health satisfaction is somewhat below average (Z = -0.53). Substance use, recreational drug use, socializing time, and many leisure activities are low relative to the cohort (multiple Z-scores < -1), indicating limited engagement in some typical social or recreational outlets; correlations of these activity variables with PSS are small in this sample.

Wearable-derived circadian and cardiovascular metrics show a well-structured, regular daily physiological pattern that is typically associated with lower perceived stress. Non-parametric circadian metrics indicate above-average interdaily stability (0.53, Z = 1.0) and very high autocorrelation at 24 hours (0.62, Z = 2.49), while intradaily variability is low (0.36, Z = -1.31). Together these indicate consistent day-to-day timing of activity and heart rate, with relatively low fragmentation of rhythm; in the study correlations, higher regularity/autocorrelation tends to relate to lower PSS (autocorrelation r ≈ -0.18). Resting heart rate (61.2 bpm, Z = 0.36) and MESOR (78.49, Z = 0.62) are modestly above the cohort mean but show only small positive correlations with PSS (r ≈ 0.06–0.14), so their contribution to elevated perceived stress is likely minor. Hourly mean heart-rate deviations reflect the expected nocturnal trough (largest negative deviations overnight) and daytime elevation peaking in the mid-to-late afternoon (acrophase ≈ 4:14 PM); these diurnal patterns are coherent rather than erratic. Sleep metrics from the wearable show a median nightly duration of about 6 h 51 m (Z = -0.41) with moderate night-to-night variability (SD ≈ 67 min, Z = -0.77) and a late median sleep onset around 00:47. Sleep quantity is slightly below the cohort mean and sleep timing is somewhat late, but there is no evidence of pronounced fragmentation or frequent napping (mean daily naps = 0.0, Z = -0.86).

Weighing the convergent evidence, the profile supports a relatively lower-to-average level of perceived stress rather than a markedly elevated one. Supporting lower/average PSS are: below-average depressive symptoms, above-average happiness, strong and stable circadian organization (high interdaily stability and very high 24-hour autocorrelation), low intradaily variability, and low substance use and napping. Factors that could elevate perceived stress are limited: trait anxiety is mildly above average and sleep duration is slightly reduced with a marginally elevated PSQI score. Many correlations between wearable metrics and PSS in this sample are small in magnitude, and the largest objective protective signal here is the participant’s highly regular daily rhythm (autocorrelation Z = 2.49), which in this cohort is associated with lower perceived stress. On balance, the pattern of data—modest anxiety but overall low depressive symptoms, above-average self-reported happiness, and pronounced circadian regularity—more strongly favors placement in the lower half of the PSS distribution.

