Self-report data indicate a mixed profile in psychological trait measures: scores on depressive symptoms (CES-D = 12, z ≈ -0.14) and trait anxiety (STAI = 38, z ≈ -0.33) are slightly below the study mean, and self-esteem is modestly above average (RSES = 39, z ≈ 0.11). These results point to relatively low self-reported core mood and trait-anxiety symptoms compared with the cohort. In contrast, the Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index is markedly elevated (PSQI = 11, z ≈ 1.98) consistent with pronounced subjective sleep disturbance. Other lifestyle reports show frequent social exercise and sports participation (exercise with others and sports both 3+ times/week, z ≈ 1.2–1.6), moderate alcohol use (beer/wine 1–2×/week, z ≈ 0.9–1.0), and generally positive health satisfaction (5/7, z ≈ 0.55). Overall, the self-report profile combines relatively low mood/anxiety symptom burden and good social/physical activity engagement with a clear signal of poor subjective sleep quality.

Wearable-derived sleep and circadian metrics provide convergent evidence of disrupted sleep timing and circadian organization despite adequate average sleep duration. Median nightly sleep duration is healthy (7 h 40 m, z ≈ 0.6), but sleep timing is late (median sleep start ≈ 01:13) and highly variable (sleep start SD ≈ 183 minutes, z ≈ 2.2). Night-to-night variability in sleep duration is also elevated (SD ≈ 159 minutes, z ≈ 1.33). Circadian features derived from heart-rate cosinor analysis show an average mesor and amplitude below the cohort mean (mesor z ≈ -0.56, amplitude z ≈ -0.51) and overall interdaily stability near average (0.41, z ≈ 0.0) with slightly reduced intraday fragmentation (intradaily variability z ≈ -0.18). Resting heart rate is relatively low (55.4 bpm, z ≈ -0.33), consistent with physical fitness and frequent exercise. Hourly aggregated heart-rate deviations show the expected nocturnal troughs and daytime peaks but with pronounced reductions during early-morning hours and midday increases; correlations between some early-morning HR deviations and PSS are small-to-moderate positive (e.g., 5–6am correlation ≈ 0.21), indicating that epochs of physiological arousal patterning have modest associations with perceived stress in this dataset.

Integrative interpretation regarding perceived stress (PSS): there are competing signals. Protective factors for lower perceived stress include below-average depression and trait-anxiety scores, elevated self-esteem, frequent social/organized exercise, and a relatively low resting heart rate. Against those, there is a robust and consistent sleep signal associated with higher stress risk: very poor subjective sleep quality (PSQI high), late average sleep timing, and notably high variability in sleep onset and duration — features that are commonly linked to elevated perceived stress and poorer stress regulation. Circadian amplitude is reduced, which in this cohort is modestly associated with higher PSS, and several sleep-timing variability metrics show small positive correlations with PSS. Alcohol use is higher than average and could represent a behavioral correlate of stress, though its direct correlations with PSS are small in this dataset. Given the magnitude of disturbed sleep (PSQI z ≈ 1.98) and very high sleep timing variability (sleep start SD z ≈ 2.2), these strong sleep-related indicators carry substantial weight for perceived stress despite relatively low scores on depression and trait anxiety. On balance — weighing the strong sleep disturbance and irregularity against protective low-mood/anxiety scores and high activity — the overall multimodal profile is more consistent with a level of perceived stress at or above the cohort median.

