Self-report measures indicate a profile broadly consistent with relatively low perceived stress. Trait anxiety (STAI-T = 24, Z = -1.71) and depressive symptoms (CES-D = 9, Z = -0.45) are both below the study mean, while self-reported happiness (5.0, Z = 1.64) and self-esteem (Z = 1.52) are elevated relative to peers. The participant reports regular, frequent exercise (three times/week or more across solo, group, and sports activities; Zs 1.07–1.58) and minimal substance use, both behaviors typically associated with lower perceived stress. Academic performance (GPAs in the mid-3.0s) and above-average health satisfaction (Z = 0.72) further support relatively effective functioning during the semester. One notable self-report risk is a PSQI score of 6 indicating some subjective sleep disturbance (commonly interpreted as clinically notable), and a pronouncedly low amount of time spent socializing with friends (15 minutes or less; Z = -2.2), which could reduce available social support — both features that can contribute to perceived stress in some individuals.

Wearable-derived physiological and circadian metrics present a mixed picture but do not strongly indicate elevated, chronic stress. Resting heart rate is relatively low (55.3 bpm, Z = -0.34) and MESOR is below average (69.4, Z = -0.62), which are typical of good cardiovascular fitness and lower basal physiological arousal. Circadian structure shows modestly reduced interdaily stability (0.37, Z = -0.33) and a small increase in intradaily variability (0.56, Z = 0.10), suggesting somewhat weaker day-to-day regularity and slightly more fragmented within-day activity; these features have small positive correlations with PSS in the study (intradaily variability corr ≈ 0.16). Hourly aggregated heart-rate deviations reveal expected nocturnal declines and pronounced evening peaks (notably 5–7 PM and late evening 10–12 PM with Z-scores up to ~3.5), consistent with elevated evening activity or arousal but not necessarily indicative of pervasive stress. Sleep duration from the wearable is slightly below average (median ≈ 6h54m, Z = -0.35) but with low night-to-night variability in sleep start time (SD ≈ 41 minutes, Z = -0.93), indicating consistent sleep timing despite somewhat short nightly duration; mean daily naps are absent.

Weighing the modalities holistically, the balance of evidence favors lower perceived stress relative to the study sample. Multiple robust indicators from self-report (low trait anxiety, low depressive symptoms, high happiness and self-esteem, frequent exercise, low substance use, and good academic and health-satisfaction outcomes) point toward placement in the lower half of the PSS distribution. Wearable signals do introduce mild countervailing concerns (subjective sleep disturbance, reduced interdaily stability, elevated evening heart-rate peaks, and notably low socializing), but these are either small in magnitude, mixed in direction, or only weakly correlated with PSS in the cohort. Overall, the preponderance of evidence supports classification in the bottom 50% of perceived stress within this study population.

